# SITUATION

AI language systems have crossed a fluency threshold. They can draft, reason, translate,
plan, and execute across an enormous range of tasks. Agentic deployment — AI that acts
on behalf of a user, not just responds to a query — is now technically feasible and
commercially active.

The dominant use pattern remains the Query Genie: a user types a question, the system
returns an answer. This is high-value but low-integration. The user provides full context
with every prompt. The system forgets everything between sessions.

---

# PROBLEM

The bottleneck is not reasoning capacity. It is context transmission.

AI systems are highly fluent and apparently understanding. This creates a false impression
of shared context. Users assume the system "knows" them. It does not. Every session
starts cold. Every agent deployed on their behalf starts blind.

The result: AI that is powerful in isolation but unreliable in continuity. An agent
dispatching a maintenance worker, briefing a care assistant, or executing a household
task fails not because it cannot reason — but because it does not know who the user is,
what constraints apply, what vocabulary is in use, or what "usual" means in this context.

This is not a prompting problem. Better prompts do not solve structural absence of context.
Platform-side memory (OpenAI Memory, Claude Projects) addresses this for single-platform
users with non-sensitive data. It does not address multi-AI workflows, professional
handover scenarios, sensitive personal context, or populations whose information cannot
be entrusted to a single vendor.

---

# IMPLICATION

Agentic AI adoption will stall at the boundary where generic reasoning meets
person-specific operational reality — unless a context transmission layer exists
that is portable, user-owned, and AI-agnostic.

The populations most exposed to this boundary are not edge cases:
- Care workers receiving a new patient with no briefing
- Dispatchers matching workers to jobs across shifting staff
- Professionals handing over to colleagues, contractors, or AI agents
- Households deploying robots or voice agents that do not know their world

For these users, the explanation cost exceeds the execution cost. This is the
Handover Threshold — the exact point where FlowZero becomes necessary.

---

# NEEDED SOLUTION

A minimal, open, portable context encoding standard and the tooling to create,
maintain, and transmit context artifacts across people, services, and AI systems.

Design constraints:
- Context must travel with the person, not the platform. This is a deliberate
  architectural bet against platform lock-in.
- The encoding must be human-writable, AI-parseable, and language-neutral.
  No dependency on any model, API, or vendor.
- The artifact (PUCK) must be loadable cold into any AI system with no
  prior configuration, training, or memory.
- The standard (CCML) must remain small enough to write by hand. Cognitive
  simplicity is a design constraint, not a nice-to-have.

Strategic niche: FlowZero leans into ephemeral and local rather than persistent and
general. Platform memory systems (cloud-based, account-bound, vendor-controlled) are
the persistent-general solution. FlowZero occupies a different space: context that
exists locally, loads on demand, and dissolves after use. This covers cases where
platform memory is unavailable, undesirable, or simply the wrong unit of abstraction —
including the mundane end of the spectrum ("where are my blue socks") where the
information is too personal for a vendor and too trivial to consciously manage, but
becomes critical the moment a robot, care worker, or voice agent needs to act in
your physical space. The niche: hyperlocal, human-specific operational context that
has no appropriate server home.

FlowZero V1 is the first implementation of this approach. It is a proof-of-concept
and a dogfooding environment — built using the very collaboration patterns it is
designed to enable.

The input problem is acknowledged and not yet solved: users who most need context
transmission are often least able to construct it. Assisted onboarding, voice capture,
and inference-from-behavior are future work. V1 validates the transmission layer.
That is the necessary first step.

The long-term aspiration: a contextual transport layer between humans, AI systems,
services, and robots — analogous to what TCP/IP provided for data networks.
Not a product. A protocol.

